  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD066489",
      "title": "Phospho-proteomic analysis of IL-13 treated human airway epithelial cell line (A549)",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Allergic asthma is a chronic inflammatory airway disease driven by the cytokine interleukin-13 (IL-13). Although IL-13 signals through the canonical JAK1/TYK2/STAT6 pathway, our understanding of the totality of IL-13-induced signaling intermediates is incomplete. To address this, we performed an unbiased phospho-proteomic analysis of IL-13-stimulated A549 human airway epithelial cells. IL-13 stimulation led to differential phosphorylation at 145 unique serine/threonine residues across 97 proteins involved in diverse cellular processes. These processes included RNA splicing, cytoskeletal remodeling, GTPase activity, and focal adhesion complex formation. Network analysis identified SRC, a non-receptor tyrosine kinase, as a potential upstream regulator of IL-13-induced changes in phosphorylation. Kinetic molecular approaches confirmed that SRC is rapidly activated following IL-13 stimulation, prior to activation of the canonical IL-13 signaling intermediate STAT6 in both human and mouse lung fibroblasts. Pharmacological inhibition of SRC reduced IL-13\u2013induced STAT6 phosphorylation and downstream gene expression in vitro. In vivo, SRC antagonism attenuated IL-13\u2013induced airway hyperresponsiveness (AHR) without significantly affecting inflammatory cell infiltration or gene expression in bronchoalveolar lavage fluid. These findings identify SRC as a novel and selective mediator of IL-13\u2013driven airway responses and suggest that targeting SRC may offer therapeutic benefit in allergic asthma.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "A549s Cells were harvested and lysed using urea lysis buffer containing 9M urea (Cell Signaling Technology, # 60055S), 20mM HEPES (Cell signaling Technology, #44686), and 1% of Phosphatase inhibitor Cocktail (Cell signaling Technology, #5870). Lysis was performed as per PTMScan protocol for cell lysis and protein digestion (cell Signaling Technology #38572).  For multiplex comparative phospho-proteomics profiling 2.5 mg of protein from each sample was reduced with dithiothreitol, alkylated with iodoacetic acid, and digested with trypsin in 8M urea. Samples were desalted on a Sep-Pak C18 cartridge (Waters) according to the PTMScan protocol for Cell Lysis and Protein Digestion (Cell Signaling Technology, #38572). Recovered peptides were enriched for phospho-peptides by using the High Select TiO2 phospho-enrichment kit (ThermoFisher, #A32993) following the vendor protocol. The eluted phospho-peptides were labeled with a TMT 11-plex isobaric labeling reagents (ThermoFisher, #A37725) using the vendor protocol with the isobaric tag assignment as provided in the supplementary table 1. After labeling the samples independently, 10% of each TMT labeled sample was pooled into an 11-plex mixture, dried and reconstituted into 0.1% formic acid and analyzed by nanoLC-MS/MS (Orbitrap Eclipse). A pooled sample of untreated controls with the 126 isobaric tag and a ratio equivalent pool of all samples with the 131C isobaric tag were included for ratio profiling with normalization and scaling of the comparative data. Comparative phospho-peptide identification and relative quantitation was accomplished by nanoLC-MSMS analysis on a Thermo Orbitrap Eclipse Mass Spectrometer coupled to Dionex Ultimate 3000 RSLCnano chromatography unit. Peptide capture and separation was done through a 5-mm nanoViper \u03bc-trap column i.d. 300 \u03bcm, C18 PepMap100, 5.0 \u03bcm, 100 \u00c5; Thermo Fisher Scientific) aligned for separation with an EASY-Spray column PepMap RSLC C18 with a 150-mm column (i.d. 75 \u03bcm, C18, 3.0 \u03bcm, 100 \u00c5). Separation proceeded at 300 nL/min with a variable gradient from 98% mobile phase A (0.1% formic acid in water) to 85% B (0.1% formic acid in acetonitrile) over 185 min with primary separation gradient ranges for 2-16% B from 15-100 min and then to 25% B at 145 min.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Data were recorded using Thermo Xcalibur 3.3.2782.34 software with a SPS (synchronous precursor selection) workflow whereby the peptide identification is accomplished via the MS2 HCD fragmentation spectra with enhanced TMT mass tag ratios capture from multiple MS3 spectra of the most abundant MS2 ions all as described previously [McAlister, Anal. Chem. 2014, 86, 14, 7150\u20137158, PMC4215866]. Data processing and relative phosphopeptide quantification was completed using with the Proteome Discoverer v 2.4 (ThermoScientific) against the uniprot-9606 (Homo sapiens FASTA database (downloaded 12-11-2020) with a TMT quantitation workflows focused on comparisons of high (99%) confidence phosphopeptides. Reporter ion correction values were used in the quantification method) from the information provided by the vendor for the TMT 11 plex kit (Lot WA310342). Dynamic modifications included oxidation of methionine and phosphorylation of serine and threonine. Static modifications included TMT6plex N-terminus peptide, TMT6plex lysine and carbamidomethyl cysteine. Dynamic N-terminal protein modifications included Acteyl, Met-loss and Met loss+acetyl. The TMT workflow included the IMP-ptmRS node in the processing workflow along with the associated modification sites node and the peptide isoform grouper in the consensus workflow to calculate the probabilities of the phosphorylation sites. In the reporter ions quantifier node only phosphorylated peptides were used for quantification and abundances were calculated using the abundance-based method. Settings of 5 for S/N ratio and 25% SPS (synchronous precursor selection) matches were used for reporter ion quantification selection. Normalization to the total phosphopeptide area in each sample and scaling to the phosphopeptides in the pool of all samples (131C isobaric tag channel) was used.",
